    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-08-30T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-08-30T12:00:00-05:00" n="690"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d690">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">511.6121/8–3050: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Douglas</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d690fn1">The Department relayed this telegram to the Embassy
                        in the Soviet Union at 6:00 p. m. on August 30.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                    <lb/>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-08-30T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 30, 1950—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1287. UK <gloss target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss> informs Embassy they have
                    decided to cease publication of <hi rend="italic">British Ally</hi> in Moscow
                    with next issue and public announcement to that effect will be made by <gloss
                        target="#t_HMG1">HMG</gloss> within a few days pending which this
                    information remains confidential.</p>
                <p>Main motivation of British is economy since production of magazine in Moscow
                    rather expensive. Circulation practically impossible <pb facs="1254" n="1238"
                        xml:id="pg_1238"/> and it no longer earns anything. British would have
                    preferred Soviets to ban it and for that reason put “hot” material in recent
                    issues but without desired effect.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Douglas</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
